  <!-- ════════ THE PATTERN — graded maturation mechanisms ════════ -->
  <section class="bb-section" id="pattern">
    <div class="bb-eyebrow">The pattern, stated plainly</div>
    <h2 class="bb-h2">The drawdowns have been getting shallower &mdash; and here is exactly how much to trust that</h2>
    <p class="bb-lead">Discount 2011, and the completed drawdowns run <strong>&minus;85%, &minus;84%, &minus;77%</strong>. Volatility has roughly halved over five years. There is a real, mechanical story for <em>why</em> a larger, more liquid asset should swing less. But &ldquo;shallower each time&rdquo; is exactly the kind of pattern that seduces you into timing the bottom &mdash; so we grade the evidence for each mechanism, out loud, and never extrapolate the next low.</p>

    <div class="bb-grades">
      <div class="bb-grade bb-grade-strong">
        <div class="bb-grade-tag">Evidence-backed</div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Capital scaling / law of large numbers.</strong> A ~$2&nbsp;trillion asset needs vastly more capital to move a given percentage than a $10&nbsp;million one did. This is arithmetic, not narrative.</li>
          <li><strong>Raised cost-basis floors.</strong> Aggregate holder cost basis sat near <strong>43.7% of the prior peak</strong> this cycle, versus a third or less historically (Galaxy) &mdash; a higher floor for mean-reversion to fall toward.</li>
          <li><strong>Volatility decay</strong> and <strong>supply absorption</strong> &mdash; large long-term-holder distribution met by comparable ETF and treasury inflows through 2026.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="bb-grade bb-grade-mid">
        <div class="bb-grade-tag">Contested &mdash; the data partly disagrees</div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>&ldquo;Institutions dampen the swings.&rdquo;</strong> The clean version of this theory <em>broke down</em> in the February 2026 sell-off: ETF redemptions <em>transmitted</em> selling straight to spot, and institutions treated Bitcoin as a high-beta tech proxy and sold it in macro stress. The stabiliser can become an accelerant. This corroborates the rising-correlation caveat below.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="bb-grade bb-grade-weak">
        <div class="bb-grade-tag">Unproven &mdash; narrative, not evidence</div>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Speculation migrating to altcoins</strong> leaving Bitcoin steadier.</li>
          <li><strong>Regulatory clarity</strong> structurally reducing panic. Plausible stories; the data does not yet support them.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="bb-smallcaps-note">Three completed cycles cannot prove a trend &mdash; a skeptic would call &ldquo;shallower each time&rdquo; an <strong>extreme case of small-sample bias</strong>, indistinguishable from three correlated random walks. We use &ldquo;has behaved,&rdquo; never &ldquo;behaves.&rdquo; History here is evidence, not destiny.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ VOLATILITY OVER TIME — computed series ════════ -->
  <section class="bb-section" id="volatility">
    <div class="bb-eyebrow">The volatility, measured</div>
    <h2 class="bb-h2">Half of what it was &mdash; still multiples of everything else</h2>
    <p class="bb-lead">Rolling annualised volatility, computed live from this site&rsquo;s price series, traces the arc: from <strong id="bbVolEarly">~150%</strong> in the early years toward <strong id="bbVolNow">~40%</strong> now &mdash; roughly half of five years ago, and today below Tesla and around Nvidia. It has fallen. It has not become small.</p>

    <div class="bb-chart-wrap bb-vol-chart" data-chart-copy data-chart-title="Bitcoin rolling annualised volatility" data-chart-filename="bitcoin-volatility-trend.png"><canvas id="bbVolChart"></canvas></div>
