      <div class="bb-vol-anchor"><span class="bb-vol-x">~3.5&ndash;4&times;</span><span class="bb-vol-l">vs a 60/40 portfolio</span></div>
    </div>

    <div class="bb-callouts">
      <div class="bb-callout">
        <h4>Two honest caveats on the decline</h4>
        <p><strong>It was not a smooth 15-year glide.</strong> An econometric read finds the 2014&ndash;2020 downtrend was statistically weak; the real compression is <em>post-2020</em> &mdash; ETFs, a trillion-dollar cap. Say &ldquo;fell sharply, chiefly since 2020,&rdquo; not &ldquo;steadily for fifteen years.&rdquo;</p>
        <p><strong>Daily-close volatility fell; intraday did not.</strong> Range-based intraday volatility stays high &mdash; near the 79th percentile of the S&amp;P&nbsp;1500 &mdash; driven by leveraged perpetual-futures liquidation cascades. That churn is largely a <em>derivatives artifact</em>, not a change in Bitcoin&rsquo;s underlying value &mdash; which is exactly why the next section matters.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ VOLATILITY ≠ RISK ════════ -->
  <section class="bb-section" id="vol-not-risk">
    <div class="bb-eyebrow">Volatility is not risk</div>
    <h2 class="bb-h2">Dispersion is not the same thing as losing your money</h2>
    <div class="bb-prose bb-prose-wide">
      <p><strong>Volatility</strong> measures dispersion &mdash; how far price ranges around its path. It is symmetric: a +40% month is penalised by the maths exactly as much as a &minus;40% month. <strong>Risk</strong>, for a long-term holder, is something else entirely: the <em>permanent</em> loss of capital. They are different quantities, and Bitcoin&rsquo;s makes the gap unusually wide.</p>
      <p>Bitcoin&rsquo;s returns are <strong>positively skewed and fat-tailed</strong> &mdash; a large share of its &ldquo;volatility&rdquo; is <em>upside</em>, especially rebounding off the Power-Law lows. A single volatility number therefore <em>overstates</em> the downside danger to someone with a long horizon. The clean way to see this: over 2020&ndash;2024 Bitcoin&rsquo;s <strong>Sortino ratio of 1.86</strong> was roughly double its Sharpe ratio &mdash; and Sortino only penalises <em>downside</em> movement. Most of the swing it ignores was the good kind.</p>
      <p class="bb-quote">As one digital-asset treasury firm puts it: <em>&ldquo;Volatility is not risk. Volatility is movement. Risk is the potential for permanent capital destruction.&rdquo;</em> &mdash; a useful framing, and worth flagging that its source has a commercial interest in you believing it.</p>
      <p class="bb-guard"><strong>The guardrail.</strong> &ldquo;Risk isn&rsquo;t volatility&rdquo; must never slide into &ldquo;Bitcoin isn&rsquo;t risky.&rdquo; There is no valuation floor; wrong sizing, a broken thesis, or being <em>forced</em> to sell at a low are all real, permanent-loss risks. The upside skew is a historical characteristic, not a guarantee that the next dip resolves upward.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ LOSS AVERSION — the fear ════════ -->
  <section class="bb-section" id="fear">
    <div class="bb-eyebrow">Why the fear is bigger than the danger</div>
    <h2 class="bb-h2">The drawdown does its damage through you, not to you</h2>
    <div class="bb-prose bb-prose-wide">
      <p>A 50% fall only becomes a 50% loss if you sell into it. Whether you do is mostly psychology, and the psychology is well-measured. <strong>Kahneman and Tversky (1979)</strong> established that losses are felt roughly <strong>twice as intensely as equivalent gains</strong> &mdash; a result replicated across some 90% of studied populations. That asymmetry is the machinery a bear market runs on.</p>
      <p>It strikes twice. It keeps newcomers from ever entering (an opportunity cost), and &mdash; the more destructive strike &mdash; it shakes existing holders out at the lows, converting a paper swing into a realised loss. And it does its worst work not in the crash but in the <strong>grind</strong>: the first sharp drop clears out leverage, a relief rally sucks people back, and then months of slow bleed, every bounce sold, break the spirit. People capitulate in the grind, not the crash.</p>
      <p><strong>Conviction has to be earned, not sold.</strong> The verified Saylor line is <em>&ldquo;Everyone gets Bitcoin at the price they deserve.&rdquo;</em> Its real-time case study arrived in 2026: a &ldquo;Saylor is selling&rdquo; headline (his firm sold 32 BTC to meet a dividend) triggered retail to panic-sell at the lows &mdash; right before the same firm rebought 1,550 BTC lower. The people the headline frightened out did precisely the thing the drawdown needed them to do.</p>
      <p class="bb-empirical">The empirical answer to the fear: the worst annualised return over <em>any</em> five-year hold has been <strong id="bbWorstHold">about +3.6%</strong> (NYDIG) &mdash; no five-year holder has lost money &mdash; and every four-year hold since 2013 has averaged 60&ndash;120% annualised (CoinMarketCap). <span class="bb-empirical-src">Cross-check the recovery maths on <a href="/the-bitcoin-horizon">The Bitcoin Horizon</a>.</span></p>
      <p class="bb-guard"><strong>The guardrail.</strong> &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t panic-sell&rdquo; is not &ldquo;diamond-hands, never sell, ever.&rdquo; Even Saylor&rsquo;s firm sold when it had to. The honest version: earned conviction, a long horizon, and <em>correct sizing so you are never forced to sell</em> let you avoid <em>panic</em> selling &mdash; contingent, always, on the thesis holding. This argues against emotional selling, not against rational portfolio decisions.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ THE COUNTERWEIGHT ════════ -->
  <section class="bb-section bb-counter" id="counter">
    <div class="bb-eyebrow">The honest counterweight</div>
    <h2 class="bb-h2">Everything above, argued against</h2>
    <p class="bb-lead">A page that only made the bull case would not be honest, and the counter-case is cited as prominently as the thesis. Here is the strongest version of the other side.</p>

    <div class="bb-counter-grid">
      <div class="bb-counter-card">
        <h4>Maturation compresses the upside too</h4>
        <p>The very forces that shrink the drawdowns &mdash; scale, liquidity, institutional depth &mdash; <em>mechanically</em> cap future returns. Even Bitcoin-favourable analysts model it: <strong>VanEck&rsquo;s base case is ~15% CAGR for 2026&ndash;2050</strong>, revised <em>down</em> from 25% a year earlier; Fidelity warns high returns &ldquo;may not persist as the asset matures.&rdquo; You cannot sell the shallower drawdowns without also selling the mid-teens returns. They are the same coin.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bb-counter-card">
        <h4>The &ldquo;uncorrelated diversifier&rdquo; claim no longer holds</h4>
        <p>Post-ETF, Bitcoin&rsquo;s correlation with equities rose to <strong>0.5&ndash;0.88</strong> (near 0.9 with the Nasdaq at points), versus roughly zero in 2018&ndash;2020. And it is not a safe haven: across S&amp;P drawdowns worse than 12%, Bitcoin lost ~35% on average while <em>gold gained ~4.7%</em> (State Street). It has behaved risk-off, then uncorrelated, then correlated, as adoption shifted &mdash; so pick no single label.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bb-counter-card">
        <h4>The reflexive floor can be clawed back</h4>
        <p>The raised cost-basis floor is real but not fixed. In a genuine panic, Galaxy notes, a 10&ndash;30% cost-basis decline can pull the implied floor from ~$40K back toward <strong>~$28K</strong>. The floor moves under stress &mdash; which is the moment you were counting on it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bb-counter-card">
        <h4>The model is a tool, not an oracle</h4>
        <p>The Power Law fits history well but is <em>not</em> a deep structural law: its exponent varies threefold by start date, and the multi-sigmoid variant that fit history best was among the <em>worst</em> out-of-sample (Baquero &amp; Menezes, 2026). Usefully, the <em>simple</em> Power Law still forecasts well at 12&ndash;24 months precisely <em>because</em> it doesn&rsquo;t overfit. Use it descriptively, never as a price oracle.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bb-trap" id="trap">
      <div class="bb-trap-tag">The prediction trap &mdash; documented, and refused</div>
      <p>Twenty-plus analysts have published a &ldquo;next bottom&rdquo; spanning roughly <strong>$25K to $68K</strong>: a deep camp near $25&ndash;37K, a consensus near $40&ndash;55K, a shallow camp near $54&ndash;68K. <strong>The width of that spread <em>is</em> the finding.</strong> When the professionals disagree by nearly 3&times;, the honest conclusion is that the bottom is unknowable &mdash; not that we should supply a twenty-first number. Today&rsquo;s price sits near the shallow end, which means further downside is entirely live if the consensus or deep camps are right. Nobody knows which. <strong>This page catalogues the guesses without joining them.</strong></p>
      <p class="bb-trap-land">Read cycles as a <strong>risk-management framework, never a timing tool</strong>. They tell you drawdowns of this magnitude happen and must be survivable in your plan. They do not tell you when.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ POSITION SIZING — the survival mechanism ════════ -->
  <section class="bb-section" id="sizing">
    <div class="bb-eyebrow">Tolerating the volatility</div>
    <h2 class="bb-h2">Position sizing is the survival mechanism</h2>
    <div class="bb-prose bb-prose-wide">
      <p>Everything above resolves into one practical lever. The reason to size a Bitcoin position carefully is not timidity &mdash; it is that <strong>risk contribution is wildly non-linear</strong>. On institutional risk-budgeting maths, a 2% allocation contributes roughly 5% of a portfolio&rsquo;s risk, but a <strong>4% allocation contributes about 14%</strong> (BlackRock); JPMorgan puts a 3.5% Bitcoin sleeve at roughly the <em>risk</em> of a 40% bond allocation. Read that as a warning about the curve, <em>not</em> a recommendation to hold 4%.</p>
      <p>Which is why the recommended caps cluster low: <strong>BlackRock 1&ndash;2%</strong>, <strong>VanEck 1&ndash;3%</strong> as the &ldquo;sweet spot,&rdquo; and Galaxy&rsquo;s finding that the biggest marginal Sharpe/Sortino gain comes just from <strong>0% &rarr; 1%</strong>. The figure and its cap belong together.</p>
      <p class="bb-synthesis">Here is the synthesis that fuses the two middle sections: <strong>oversizing guarantees the loss-aversion shakeout.</strong> Hold more than you can watch fall 77%, and the psychology does the rest &mdash; you sell at the low, converting volatility into permanent loss. Correct sizing is precisely what lets conviction survive the drawdown, which is the only way you are still holding to capture the returns. Sizing is not a tax on the thesis; it is what makes the thesis survivable.</p>
      <p class="bb-handoff">The <em>how much</em> &mdash; the Kelly criterion, why its raw answer (~65%) is absurd, and why fractional Kelly lands nearer ~10% &mdash; belongs to its own page. <a href="/how-much-bitcoin">How Much Bitcoin?</a> owns that calculation; this page owns only the reason it matters.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

